title: For Sale:  BENELLI I-12 FOR SALE
postcontent:
The Franchi I-12 is a semi-automatic shotgun chambered in 12 gauge. The I-12 comes in four finishes, Realtree APG HD, Advantage Max-4 HD, walnut and black Synthetic to meet a variety of hunting needs.
It uses an inertia driven bolt, so bolt is basically fixed when the firing pin punches forward and strikes the primer. The primer sends a charge into the gunpowder and it explodes and releases gases that propel the shot through the barrel. Once the shot and gas exit, a backwards force then drives through the gun (recoil/vibrations). When the force reaches the bolt housing, the bolt is then driven back until the inertia spring catches and sends it forward. This system replaces systems that other semi-autos use where gas or the initial explosion drive the bolt back. And, since the gases can’t seep through into the chamber there won’t be any carbon-build up.
Features include a Twin Shock Absorber (TSA) recoil pad that deeply compresses with the recoil, soaking up the kick and spreading recoil energy over a wider area of the shooter’s shoulder

title: For Sale:  Colt M16A1 US Property Marked Transferable M16 A1
postcontent: Selling an unbelievable find, one of the few US Property marked transferable M16's in the United States. This is an all factory original machine gun that was built by Colt in Hartford, CT in the late 1970's. This was sold to the Federal Government, and the widely accepted story is that these were issued to the Department of Energy (DOE) to protect nuke sites across the country. A small number of these were sold to civilians in the late 1980's.As you can see, this was a carried weapon and has some great patina and lots of character. It is so hard to find a M16 with honest wear - it is actually much harder than finding a new one. This rifle mechanically is in excellent condition including the bore. It appears to have been fired very little.One of the things that attracts me to this rifle is with the US Property markings, it is 'the very thing' for so many different military builds that you could do, like a MK18 Mod 0 build, or a MK12 SPR build, this is the exact lower - it wouldn't even be a clone.

title: For Sale:   Rare S&W Model 1950 .44 Target Revolver 4" Barrel
postcontent: Serial #S98020, .44 Special, 4” barrel with an excellent, bright bore. This is a very handsome 5-screw revolver that has matching numbers on the frame, cylinder, barrel, extractor, and yoke with the metal retaining 98-99% of the original blue finish that has some trace silvering on the muzzle and a mild turn-ring on the cylinder. The target hammer and trigger have nearly all of their original color case-hardening remaining with a few traces of gray along the edges, and there is some further minor fading along the edges of the ramp front sight with red insert. The checkered, diamond-center grips are correct but numbered to a different gun and are in excellent condition with only a few extremely minor handling marks and some mild flattening of the points. The revolver is housed in its original, “1926 Model” marked, pre-war two-piece gold box which is numbered to the gun on the bottom and surcharged “4” over the “6 1/2” on the label end. The revolver is accompanied by a 2016 dated S&W factory letter listing a ship date of January 26, 1954 to Evaluators Ltd., Triangle, VA (Evaluators Ltd. was a law enforcement dealer with close ties to the FBI at nearby Quantico, VA). Additionally, the letter makes notice of the fact that S&W was actively using up their back stock of older boxes at the time this revolver was shipped. This is an extremely nice example of a very desirable .44 Target that rates excellent condition overall. FFL or C&R
